values:
My stupid pneumonia cough is back so I downed some cough syurp with codine in it and I feel the effects kicking in, but i'm in the mood to write after reading oodles of blogs from people who are in the process of becoming doctors. &nbsp;My two cents are to be thrown in.
Why am I reading such blogs? &nbsp;Because my district screwed me. &nbsp;Like bff says, &quot;in education you know every district will screw you, granted each will screw you in a unique way, but they will screw you none-the-less&quot; &nbsp;My district chose to do so in the form of not granting me the agreeded contract after my certification went through so I get paid as a sub instead of a teacher even though I'm doing the work of a teacher. &nbsp;

So of course I sigh and try to find out the greater lesson in it all. &nbsp;I found it ironic how i had finally come to terms with being a teacher. &nbsp;I reluctantly took the job after swearing off teaching and amazingly found that i did like teaching, i was actually good at it. &nbsp;One good thing is that it renewed my faith in both myself and my ability to be a successful teacher. &nbsp;So there I was finally at peace with that part of my life, finally saying, &quot;ya know.... I COULD do this for the rest of my life.&quot; &nbsp;Then BAM, I get screwed. &nbsp;So I'm trying to acertain what exatally I'm to do about this, what is the lesson? &nbsp;Is the universe telling me to fight to be a teacher, or is it giving me a chance to leave education without feeling like a failure. &nbsp;Then hubby pointed out that the universe was not in fact trying to get me but rather giving me multiple options all of which are &quot;right&quot; it's just a matter of what I want to choose to do. &nbsp;This got me thinking. &nbsp;What do i really WANT to do. &nbsp;Well shit, that's a hard thing to decide. &nbsp;I kept finding myself with a cup full of &quot;if's and's &amp; buts&quot; so I tried to eliminate all variables except what i actually desired to do. &nbsp;I looked at it through the lens of if $ and time weren't an issue what would I do. &nbsp;Without hesitation I knew, I'd be a doctor.

When I first started college that was my plan, but i thought I could never afford it, it took too long, and I wasn't smart enough. &nbsp;I quit. &nbsp;I went the &quot;easy&quot; route and it's always been there. &nbsp;

The thing is, I would be a kickass doctor. &nbsp;Under pressure and in &quot;gross&quot; situations i totally hold my shit together and am a calming force. &nbsp;Here's the thing too, I'm a woman who comes from a poor family. &nbsp;I know what it's like to be pushed to the sidelines. &nbsp;There this definate class distinction (usually) between physicians and patients and I want to bridge that gap. &nbsp;

&nbsp;I've been rolling around this post in my head for weeks. &nbsp;More like I've been rolling around my feeling about my current job and have come up with some startling conclusions.

First a brief update. &nbsp;I swore off teaching. &nbsp;Like big time. &nbsp;I looked for teaching jobs out here in CA, but wasn't disappointed when none landed in my lap. &nbsp;Instead I ended up doing temp work as a receptionist and loved every damn minute of it. &nbsp;I was so grateful for being out of education and working elsewhere made that ever more clear. &nbsp;I could see all the faults and cracks and recite the many reasons I hated teaching, how it sucked the life out of me. &nbsp;My new job loved me. &nbsp;I was amazing and could do no wrong. &nbsp;It was so damn nice to have someone tell me I was doing a good job, to come home and have NOTHING to work on. &nbsp;Things were........ &quot;good.&quot; &nbsp;

Then I met A. at my daughters back to school night. &nbsp;Her son is in boo's class. &nbsp;A. is a VP at a middle school and we hit it off right away, 2 weeks later I find myself standing in front of a class of students. &nbsp;The one place I swore I'd never be. &nbsp;Whaaaaaaaatttt??

I now teach Environmental Science and US History to 11/12th graders and um...... I freaking like it. &nbsp;DAMN IT!! &nbsp;I'm actually not being sarcastic here for once. &nbsp;I hate teaching! &nbsp;It DOES suck the life out of you. &nbsp;The only way to really do it well is to totally throw yourself into it. &nbsp;The kids are bastards and fuck with you just because, and then think you're the greatest, and then do stupid ass shit, never-ending grading, ever changing curriculum expectations, too many kids in a class, screwy parents, not enough money, a million other things. &nbsp;Teaching is going to be the death of me. &nbsp;It's thankless and no matter what you do there's 100 more things you need to get done. &nbsp;I don't want it to be my thing. &nbsp;I want something else to be my &quot;thing.&quot; &nbsp;Something that rewards a job well done, that is logical and orderly. &nbsp;But..... it's not to be. &nbsp;Some part of me seeks out that chaos and I have to admit, not having it at the other job was freaking BOOORRRRIIINNNNGGGG!!! &nbsp;Every day was the same. &nbsp;There were no challenges, nothing pushing my creativity. &nbsp;Just day in and day out. &nbsp;I found myself getting so restless. &nbsp;At first I couldn't figure out why. &nbsp;Then it started to dawn on me, a part of me was missing teaching. &nbsp;I refused to admit it for a while. &nbsp;But the universe is unforgiving when trying to teach you a lesson and of course began to throw all sorts of educational things at me. &nbsp;

The first few days were hell and each day I was sure it was going to be my last and i wasn't going to come back. &nbsp;The kids SUCKED! &nbsp;That's another post though, but then - there was that moment when I was up there all excited because I was teaching them about state vs. federal rights and they were all in the discussion and coming up with awesome comments and questions and I was flying high. &nbsp;Now if this was a movie staring a hard nosed teacher determined to not give up on the inner city kids there would be a segway showing one of them faced with &nbsp;the opportunity to commit a drive bye or something and they'd reflect on my words of wisdom and turn away from it. &nbsp;But it's not that movie and sure enough the very next day they were bastards again. &nbsp;Kids are so fickle. &nbsp;But it reminded me of that feeling I lost for years.... that feeling you get when they're actually LISTENING to you, and you're talking about something that you feel is totally important and you're showing them WHY it's important and they GET IT! &nbsp;I have to admit, teaching elementary school did not give me many of those moments. &nbsp;In fact, it robbed me of all my self confidence. &nbsp;I still haven't sorted out how much of that came from teaching in Louisiana, and how much of it was from teaching elem. school. &nbsp;Regardless, teaching HS again is much better than elem. &nbsp;I don't want to like it, but I'm beginning to see that I will probably always crave it. &nbsp;Damn.

At this moment I'm sitting at a makeshift desk surrounded by uhaul boxes and cheap plastic bins which are filled with the contents of my life. &nbsp;In 5 days said boxes will be loaded on a uhaul and we'll be on our way to our new home on the other side of the country. &nbsp;I'm awash with so many different conflicting yet equally strong feelings that I have no idea where to begin.

I've had a few &quot;major moves&quot; in my life. &nbsp;The obligitory &quot;off to college&quot; move, though major, I always knew it was temporary. &nbsp;A means to an end. &nbsp;The move back to havasu felt that way as well. &nbsp;The first BIG move was to North Carolina where I packed up what little I owned and treked into the unknown. &nbsp;BFF and I arrived at the house (which I had no idea what to expect) and both started to cry - the boy had come through and I was going to live in a decent house! &nbsp;I lived there for 4 years, 3 3/4 years longer than the relationship which led me there. &nbsp;

Next major moved happened in a whirlwind, split second decision which landed me in podunk Louisiana next door to my soon to be ex-boyfriends parents. &nbsp;That moved happened so fast that I didn't really have too much time to worry about it, and work started the next day so it was months until I was able to actually process it all. &nbsp;4 years later, husband, daughter and I are about to embark to California. &nbsp;This move is markedly different in that we both want to go, it's been planned for ages, etc etc. &nbsp;Instead of leaving an old life and beginning a new, it's more of a continuation of our family. &nbsp;It's the reaching of a goal we'd set together - which was to one day move closer to family and friends whom all live in the West. &nbsp;

Despite all this, I'm finding myself a bit scared and overwhelmed. &nbsp;What if it sucks. &nbsp;Plain and simple. &nbsp;I don't think it will, but what if it does. &nbsp;On top of that, I've been in a bit of a social isolation mood out here. &nbsp;The people are different than me, sooo different. &nbsp;I'm surrounded by people who still refer to others as &quot;he black ya know&quot; in whispered tones. &nbsp;Where to not eat crawfish with ever other meal is a bit sacraligeous. &nbsp;There's a famous book out here (forgive me if I already mentioned it) &quot;Who's your mama, are you catholic, and can you make a rou&quot; &nbsp;That's pretty much what people ask you upon meeting from one degree to another. &nbsp;Who's your kin, who do you know. &nbsp;I digress, but let's just say that this place though interesting, to me will be chalked up as a bit of a participant observation in my unwritten sociology book :) &nbsp;

It's easy to say I had few good friends out here, and while in NC, though I had more friends, it was hard to maintain them in a military town which transfered people in and out with the drop of a hat. &nbsp;Needless to say I'm going on almost 8 years without having what I would consider &quot;proper&quot; friends. &nbsp;This of course not counting friends from before the moves. &nbsp;And here I am about to enter a place where I should be able to actually make real friends and I find myself feeling a bit like a freshman about to enter high school for the first time. &nbsp;I'm a bit afraid that I'm too out of practice to make any real friends. &nbsp;Plus I'm a bit negative, and not really very cool, and oddly enough really shy. &nbsp;

I guess what I'm looking for is to round out my life. &nbsp;I'm blessed that this is the stage of my life I find myself in. &nbsp;But I am overwhelmed at the thought. &nbsp;

&nbsp;So I thought I'd be all bad ass and work out today. &nbsp;Yeah I know, what was I thinking. &nbsp;Here's the scene: &nbsp;Me in my &quot;livingroom/kitchen/super cramped area&quot; &nbsp;filled with parts of bella's social studies project remains. &nbsp;I fire up the wii and put in my new biggest loser game. &nbsp;I'm all pumped up. &nbsp;I step on the balance board to calculate my weight - oh wait, i should take off my shoes and jacket so it'll be accurate.... gulp, that can't be right.....184 holy crap. &nbsp;Okay, okay, not a problem, I mean i AM working out so it'll go down right? &nbsp;Sigh. &nbsp;Focus nikki, focus. &nbsp;Alright, I do one of the challenges to see where I'm at. &nbsp;I choose what I think will be a decent challenge and get going. &nbsp;5 minutes of a football run, that shouldn't be too bad. &nbsp;OMG IT WAS SOOOO TO BAD!! &nbsp;But wait, it didn't stop there, that was just round ONE!! &nbsp;Hmmm, I wonder how many rounds there are, it doesn't say, but I can't stop now cuz if I do it'll mess up my score. &nbsp;So I start the second round, damn my remote just fell out of my pockets. &nbsp;Okay, I'll take a quick break and change into better pants.... now back for round 3. &nbsp;Ohhh, I'm tired - maybe this is the last round. &nbsp;I sit down and rest, but it's starting again so instead of running I just wiggle the remote - but I gotta wiggle it really really fast which is tiring in itself but it must be over soon right? &nbsp;And how come I'm still in 5th place with cheating?!! &nbsp;Okay, round 4 (continue wiggling)..... skip ahead to the final round ROUND 8!!!!! &nbsp;and I'm exhausted and all I did was sit and shake the remote up and down really fast so it thought I was running. &nbsp;UGGGGHHHHH!!! &nbsp;I get tired cheating at wii exercise. &nbsp;That's definatly NOT a good sign, but in all fairness, moving your arms up and down really fast for 40 minutes should count for exercise I think :)

I rested some more and did some super light yoga with the game. &nbsp;And now I'm sore. &nbsp;This is going to be a loooonnnngggg journey. &nbsp;

For some reason I've always wanted to be a runner. &nbsp;Which is weird since i really hate to run. &nbsp;Tomorrow I start my &quot;couch to 5k&quot; program which claims to get non-runners to the point of being able to run a 5k. &nbsp;It alternates with walking and jogging starting out really slow. &nbsp;walk for 90 sec. run for 60 etc. etc. for a total of 20 minutes. &nbsp;I wasn't scared at first, but after my wii fiasco I'm afraid someone will find me on the side of the road dead from a heart attack after 10 sec. of jogging. &nbsp;If anyone can die from running it will be me. &nbsp;

Friday we had a snow day. &nbsp;Here in Louisiana. &nbsp;I couldn't believe it! &nbsp;Especially when it didn't actually snow. &nbsp;Then tonight I found out that school is also closed monday due to low water pressure. &nbsp;I actually found this out by accident on facebook. &nbsp;Crazy how the world works. &nbsp;See I always forget to charge my phone so it's in the depths of my purse, silent and dead hence I didn't get a phone call from the parish. &nbsp;Well, I did, but I didn't hear it. &nbsp;Anyway, put bella to be and was messing around on fb and I see that one of my coworkers posts there's no school tomorrow so I check it out and sure enough, no school. &nbsp;The parish is &quot;running low&quot; on water and so the water will be turned off tonight at 10pm. &nbsp;But no one knows when it'll be turned back on. &nbsp;No water = no school. &nbsp;Now, the no school part is great, but the no water part sucks. &nbsp;I'm not sure why we're low since we've had so much rain it's been flooding like crazy here. &nbsp;Not to mention we're right along the mississippi. &nbsp;There's no mention if something's broken and they've got to turn off the water to fix it or what the deal is, but no one in the whole parish will have water as of 10pm tonight. &nbsp;Oh the joys of living in backwoods LA.

&nbsp;So tonight bella is at a hornet's game with jensen. &nbsp;She was able to get cheap tickets cuz she's in 4-H and they had some sorta special thing. &nbsp;Jensen being a basketball fan he was stoked as was bella. &nbsp;I on the other hand wasn't looking foreward to spending a night after work in a loud stadium blah blah so i decided it was to be &quot;their&quot; night (when in reality it was a &quot;mom is free from everyone&quot; night). &nbsp;I love my family deeply, but oh how I'm loving tonight. &nbsp;I went and did the girlie mani-pedi, caught up on Lost and talked with my best bud for hrs. &nbsp;Which is sorta where this post is coming from. &nbsp;

It's odd when you get old. &nbsp;I'm reflecting on all the random tangents our conversation took and how in so many ways though we're talking about the economy and the state of education today we're still talking about the same things that we did 20 years ago..... people who suck, yearning to find people who don't suck, relationships, where we're living and where we want to go, boys and pets (no, not that the boys are our pets but they both came up in the same conversation haha). &nbsp;Even now we &quot;talk&quot; like we did in H.S. in that we can finish each others sentences and jump from one topic to the other in some sort of seamless dance. &nbsp;We'd get teased about how we talked. &nbsp;Here's an example:
Me: &quot;omg did you hear&quot;
Her: &nbsp;&quot;yeah I know!&quot;
Me: &nbsp;&quot;it's like that thing&quot;
Her: &nbsp;&quot;totally, and then it's like&quot;
Me: &nbsp;&quot;I KNOW! &nbsp;why is that&quot;
Her: &quot;totally&quot;
and that would litterally be our conversation, the thing is .... we knew exactally what the other was talking about and were able to interpert it and analyze it the same way...without word. &nbsp;I can't remember who it was, but one of our classmates said it was like we read each others mind. &nbsp;We still do that even now.

I love my best friend. &nbsp;No matter where we are, we're going through the same thing. &nbsp;We get each other. &nbsp;You know those friends you have who have your back first and ask questions later.... that's her. &nbsp;If someone needed to be offed, she'd do it. &nbsp;Okay, not really but it's one of those things where the bond is there that even if the friend is wrong, they're your friend first. &nbsp;I'm not sure if I'm making sense. &nbsp;We're the ying to the others yang. &nbsp;I'm a hypochondriac, she's deathly afraid of doctors. &nbsp;I'm an organization freak, she's.... um.... not haha. &nbsp;When she's down and avoiding phone calls I know how to drag her out to be social. &nbsp;When&nbsp;i'm going through craziness in my life she knows how to calm me down. &nbsp;We bitch about our parents, siblings, ex's, currents, together and it's all good. &nbsp;She remembers things for me and I find things for her. &nbsp;I miss her. &nbsp;I miss living in the same town as her sooo much. &nbsp;

It just gets me thinking about how important those friendships are. &nbsp;How rare they are and how grateful I am to have her in my life. &nbsp;I think some people go through life without having that. &nbsp;In more ways than one I think we've saved each others lives, and in more ways than one I think we've added a spark to each others lives. &nbsp;And for that, I'm eternally grateful. &nbsp;And someday, we will fly off to Europe on a whim, and as soon as she starts that writing commune in Mexico I'll be the first in line....even though I don't write haha

Here's to good friends

I called in sick today because, well I'm sick.&nbsp; Normally I hate wasting sick&nbsp;days when I'm ill because what's the fun of staying home if you can't actually ENJOY it.&nbsp; But having fought this cold for what feels like months I finally broke down and allowed myself to sleep until bella came home at 3:30.&nbsp; The drawback is that it's now 11:30pm and I have to go to work tomorrow buy my brain/body thinks it's wakie time.&nbsp; So I'm left with the inability to sleep and random thoughts roaming my brain.

We're going to get married on a yacht off of Newport Beach most likely.&nbsp; It's&nbsp;funny, I was never one of those girls that "played married" or planned out her wedding by the ripe age of 9.&nbsp; The first marriage was meant to be cliche hence the drive thru&nbsp;wedding chapple in Vegas.&nbsp;&nbsp;When Johnny talked marriage I was excited, but couldn't conceptualize it probably because somewhere in the back of my brain I knew that things&nbsp;just weren't right, but oh did I fight that one for a few years.&nbsp; Fast foreward to now.&nbsp; We knew we wanted to get married out west since both of our families were from that area.&nbsp; We both knew we wanted an outside wedding as well and that was about as far as I got.

To me, most weddings suck&nbsp;considering the amount of money people put into them.&nbsp; There's always the fake fancy food and matching chair covers and useless party favors on the table.&nbsp; A pretend paparazzi floating about hoping to take the perfect pics.&nbsp; The ceremony is usually no better.&nbsp; Alright, we all sit there and wait till the bride comes down the isle.&nbsp; Usually you can't here what the guys's saying but there are a few i do's and it's off to the previously mentioned party.&nbsp; There are flowers that will&nbsp;soon die&nbsp;decorating every possible place and the colors are always something bland.&nbsp; People don't start dancing until they're drunk and you're filled in a room that is composed of mostly strangers and relatives that no one has seen in years but are somehow obligated to come.&nbsp; This is through the eyes of&nbsp; the average guest.&nbsp; And to think that they spent $150 per person for this event.&nbsp; I know I know, the people in the wedding, those who are celebrating their new lives are loving every minute of it and truely that's what's important.&nbsp; But often I wonder how much of the&nbsp;wedding comes from our complete socialization into how a wedding is SUPPOSE to be.&nbsp; There's an&nbsp;entire industry dedicated to showing you how you should do your wedding.&nbsp; And I wonder how many people would enjoy going to their own wedding if they were merely a guest.&nbsp;&nbsp;

My first concern in planning my wedding was the reception site because i don't care how many flowers and sashes you put around something if the place has a dorky moose head hanging from&nbsp;the wall it's just not going to work.&nbsp; I love 2 things aesthetically, color and nature.&nbsp; Color as in Picasso's Woman in Front of&nbsp;A Mirror and nature as in well.........nature.&nbsp; It's hard to really have either of those two things at a reception short of cover the walls of a reception hall in lots of fabric and, well,&nbsp;most places don't seem to be fly with that.&nbsp; And then there's the question of flowers, what to put where without spending a million dollars.&nbsp; Does anyone have any IDEA how much it costs to have flowers everywhere for a wedding........flowers, the ones that are going to die in a week, the thing that I never have around my house at all.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;

So it becomes overwhelming because you begin to feel like you've got to conform to some sorta mold.&nbsp; It's like when you're pregnant and strangers come up to you in the store and touch your belly and tell you&nbsp;techniques on brest-feeding.&nbsp; Except now they touch the ring and tell you the name of a good photographer.&nbsp; And you begin to think if people would talk if you chose fake flowers, if there'd be a scandal at the water cooler if you decided to not put foil embossment on your wedding invitations.&nbsp; It's retarded because everyone gets sucked into it.&nbsp;&nbsp;And in the end they all look the same!&nbsp; After&nbsp;untold hours of the bride agonizing over which shade of green to include in the place settings ..........it still looks the same as every other wedding.&nbsp; All that stress, all the arguments the couple probablly had&nbsp;over who to sit where, was really all for naught.&nbsp;&nbsp;

I know this, and yet I'm about to embark upon the hellish journey of becoming "one of them."&nbsp; So I'm trying to not fall into that wedding planning trap of insanity.&nbsp; I want something that's fun and something that's us.&nbsp; Screw place cards people sit where you want.&nbsp; Decorations, we're on a freaking boat, look outside :)&nbsp; Food, serve yourself but before you do, let's load up on the drinks and turn the music up.&nbsp; That's my idea of a good time.&nbsp; Oh and the yacht has a poker table - I don't play poker, but I would at my wedding.&nbsp; Hell I'd be the freaking dealer - just give me one of those hats.&nbsp; Why?&nbsp; because it looks like fun and I've never been to a wedding where people played poker.&nbsp; And I was thinking on the 3rd deck of having a kids room with cool games and such for them to play with.&nbsp; That way the parents could have fun as well as the kids.&nbsp; I always hated being a kid at a wedding.&nbsp; I had to get all dressed up and couldn't have any fun.&nbsp;&nbsp;Maybe I'll even rent a salsa dancer to give us all lessons, that would be fun for me hehehe.&nbsp; I've always wanted to learn to salsa dance and it'd get people up off their chairs.&nbsp; So I'm open to ideas and suggestions.&nbsp; Things you've always wanted to see at a wedding or ways to&nbsp;make a wedding better.&nbsp; I'm set on the yacht though :)&nbsp;It can hold up to 150 people and has 3 stories.&nbsp; It'll be in the summer, sunset,&nbsp;trolling alongside the beach.

let's get this party started :)&nbsp;

KT wrote a piece in which I was in it.&nbsp; It dealt with the chaos that was the birth of mini-me.&nbsp; It was beautiful.&nbsp; At the end there was a comment about how despite our collective fucked up upbringings that mini-me was going to know she was loved.&nbsp; No matter what.

Tonight she and I had movie night.&nbsp; Godbless vacations, I find I actually have time to enjoy things such as movie night :)&nbsp; So we got in our pj's, climbed into my bed and ate endless amounts of popcorn while watching movies.&nbsp; It was a perfect moment.&nbsp; Her and I chatting, cuddling, laughing all of that good stuff.&nbsp; Perfect.&nbsp; And when she fell asleep I just sat looking at her and I realized something amazing.&nbsp; She knows she's loved.&nbsp; I've succeeded somehow, some way.&nbsp; She knows.&nbsp;&nbsp;

I was reminded of moments growing up.&nbsp; My mom is an amazing lady.&nbsp; She pulled us outta hell through sheer might.&nbsp; She beat the odds and because of that I'm here and the person that I am today.&nbsp; But unfortunatlly that came at a cost.&nbsp; She was so busy keeping us safe, putting food on our table etc. that she had so little left.&nbsp; And I think a part of her feared that if she relaxed a bit, if she showed emotion she'd crack and not be able to save us from another statistic.&nbsp; I remember the nightmares, some of which still haunt me when I close my eyes.&nbsp; Hell, my life was a nightmare, but it was the worst at night.&nbsp; All I wanted was my mom's arms around me, hugs, reassuring words that only a mother can give in times like that (note:&nbsp; a father can do this as well of course, but there wasn't one able to do that for me).&nbsp; But I never got those hugs or words.&nbsp; When the nightmares were especially bad I'd BEG to sleep in her bed to no avail, so back to my prison I went.&nbsp; I don't hold it against her, she did what she needed to do to survive and I truely believe without that armor of steel she was encased with we wouldn't have survived.&nbsp; But it made it tough to love so to speak.&nbsp; To hug, for sooooooooooo long it was offensive to me in a way to be hugged.&nbsp; Awkward.&nbsp;&nbsp;

And then came mini-me.&nbsp; And I couldn't help but hug her and hold her tight.&nbsp; If there was one thing I wanted it was for her to know she's loved.&nbsp; To feel safe, to be able to have me, to have my heart and know that she was the most important thing in the world to me.&nbsp; Tonight I saw that she knew.&nbsp; That I was successful.&nbsp; And I felt blessed beyond belief.

A few weeks ago she came home and told me about her friend Brianna.&nbsp; She was shocked because Brianna said she hated her life.&nbsp; Bella just couldn't comprehend that concept..........hating one's life.&nbsp; I wanted to cry - I remember being her age and wishing that my nightmare was over even if it meant death.&nbsp; And yet here was mini-me telling me how she felt so bad for Brianna.&nbsp; Bella tells me how much she loves her life.&nbsp; All the people that love her - she felt fortunate.&nbsp; She tells me that I'm the best mom that ever lived.&nbsp; That she knows I love her more than anything in the world.&nbsp; I almost cried.&nbsp; The next day she told me she talked to Brianna and she thinks she cheered her up.&nbsp; She told Brianna how Johnny had been in the hospital a few times and how much it scared her and that it was okay to be scared and if she ever wanted a hug, she was there to give her a hug.&nbsp; Bella's 7 years old.&nbsp; I don't know how she turned out so amazing.&nbsp; I'm in constant awe of her capacity to love life and care so much about others.&nbsp;&nbsp;

So here I sit with mini-me crashed in my bed and I can't help but feel like the luckiest human being in the history of the world

For the last yr. my life has been unusual, uncommon, unpredictable.&nbsp; It's hard to explain.&nbsp; Especially lately.&nbsp; I feel as though I've lost my creativity somewhere along the lines and I don't know if it's because of events and the general feeling of "lost self" or the meds.&nbsp; Don't get me wrong, my meds have helped me in ways I can't begin to articulate, but oddly there's a sense of loss there.&nbsp; I read old pre-med posts and I am amazed at my words.&nbsp; Yet now, I do feel a bit dulled.&nbsp; The creative juices don't seem to flow like they use to.&nbsp; If only you could harness the creativity of being bi-polar and lose all the rest hehehe.&nbsp; Sigh

But the events of the last year have sorta forced me to see myself more clearly than I have in a long time.&nbsp; I think it also has to do with living alone.&nbsp; Maybe it's just that I'm on vacation giving me the permission to be reflective and not feel guilty about neglecitng evil lesson plans.&nbsp; I don't know.&nbsp; But I'm sure that has to do with why I'm processing so many thing finally.&nbsp;&nbsp;

I've always lost myself in men.&nbsp; The classic scene.... independent girl meets boy, boy is cool, 3 yrs. later girl wakes up in a foreign place kicking herself for letting it happen again.&nbsp; Okay, maybe it's not classic, but for me it is.&nbsp; I'm just being honest.&nbsp; It's hard for people to admit their faults besides the forgivable ones like, "i snore" etc.&nbsp;&nbsp;

I could pull some freud outta my ass and explain it using terms from my childhood and fucked up dad and wanting to be loved, abandonment issues, blah blah.&nbsp; Which I'm sure all plays a role, but the plain and simple fact is i'm 31 years old and that's just an excuse to justify bad habits of mine.&nbsp; The simple fact is for whatever reason I feel I should give all of me to the person I love to prove to them that my love is true.&nbsp; I try to be the "perfect"&nbsp; fill in the blank.&nbsp; I struggle and cling and claw and drag love out in an attempt to believe that it actually exists all the while expecting to be dissapointed.&nbsp; As if "love" is the only thing that matters, being with someone is the only way to give life meaning.&nbsp; Which is bullshit I know, but knowing and doing are always two seperate things and marring the two always seemed damn near impossible for me.&nbsp;&nbsp;

But I feel like I'm ready to let that go.&nbsp; Acceptence that I'm never going to get the reassurance I need.&nbsp; That's not said in a negative, defeatist way.&nbsp; More from the positive angle that I see what I expect will never be enough for me.&nbsp; That I have to learn to accept that in order to lose that perception.&nbsp; Not that no one will ever love me enough, but rather that I would always want more, always be uncertain, always look for the darkside of it all and in doing so I force it out fufilling my prophecy so to speak.

I wonder the thoughts of others, the fears they experience in regards to love and relationships.&nbsp; The true ups and downs not the vague, "it's hard so you just have to work through the tough times."&nbsp; We're so vague when it comes to the actual experience of relationships.,&nbsp; That uncertainty, those insecurities, fears.&nbsp; The things that cross your mind in the midst of an argument.&nbsp; What you think when you go to bed.&nbsp; How you feel when you see them at random times, doing mundane things.,&nbsp; The figurative and the literal perceptions fo a relationship.&nbsp;&nbsp;

So I'm back to finding myself again.&nbsp; That's so cliche, "finding myself"&nbsp; I regret writing it - I'm back to remembering to live my life again.&nbsp; To read my books.&nbsp; To argue about&nbsp; the inequities between policy and practice of special education and inclusion.&nbsp; Downloading music, painting my place how I want.&nbsp; watching movies.&nbsp; sleeping late.&nbsp; All those things that I manage to take from myself of my own accord.&nbsp;&nbsp;

There's really no ending to this post as there's not a conclusion to my thoughts, my search, my life
